      "span_text": "When the UK adopted price-cap regulation as its incentive mechanism for all privatised utilities, its original proponents recognised that resetting the X factor at regulatory review raised complex issues of how closely it should be related to the utility's achieved performance without destroying incentives and how much it could be decoupled from that performance without raising populist objections. suggest that, in large-scale network industries where regional natural monopoly characteristics are important, it would be difficult to avoid relating the X factor to some measure of company performance, especially the rate of return on capital, and consequently yardstick performance measures would become extremely important."
